Read in BRFSS 2023 Data for demostration

BRFSS_2023=read_xpt("LLCP2023XPT.zip") %>% 
  subset(select = c('FMONTH','SEQNO','SEXVAR','GENHLTH','_EDUCAG','_INCOMG1','HEIGHT3','WEIGHT2')) %>% 
  subset(HEIGHT3 < 7777) %>% 
  mutate(feet=substr(HEIGHT3,1,1), inches=substr(HEIGHT3, 2, nchar(HEIGHT3))) %>% 
  mutate(height=as.numeric(feet)*12+as.numeric(inches)) %>% 
  mutate(bmi= (WEIGHT2 / (height ^ 2)) * 703) %>% 
  subset(WEIGHT2 < 7777) %>% 
  slice(1:10000)
  
  
BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR <- ordered(BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR,
levels = c(1,2),
labels = c("Male", "Female"))

BRFSS_2023$GENHLTH <- ordered(BRFSS_2023$GENHLTH,
levels = c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,9,NA),
labels = c("Excellent", "Very good","Good","Fair","Poor","Dont know/Not Sure","Refused","Not asked or Missing"))

BRFSS_2023$`_EDUCAG` <- ordered(BRFSS_2023$`_EDUCAG`,
levels = c(1,2,3,4,9),
labels = c("Did not graduate High School", 
           "Graduated High School",
           "Attended College or Technical School",
           "Graduated from College or Technical School",
           "Dont know/Not sure/Missing"))

Basic statistical testings

Two Sample T Test for continuous variable

#Perform T test to check on the means of BMI by sex
#H0 (Null hypothesis): Off the 10,000 participants of BRFSS 2023, the average BMIs of male and female participants were same.
#H1 (alternative hypothesis): Off the 10,000 participants of BRFSS 2023, the average BMIs of male and female participants were NOT the same.

#Generate boxplot to check the distribution of BMI by sex
ggplot(BRFSS_2023, aes(x=SEXVAR, y=bmi)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

#Perform t-test (two sample t test)
t.test(as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$bmi)~as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR),
       alternative = c("two.sided"),
       mu = 0, paired = FALSE, var.equal = FALSE,
       conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$bmi) by as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR)
## t = 0.5897, df = 9945.4, p-value = 0.5554
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 1 and group 2 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1795597  0.3340806
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 1 mean in group 2 
##        28.74336        28.66610
#Based on the two sample t test finding, the p-value of comparing the mean of BMI by sex was 0.5554, which is greater than 0.05. Therefore, we failed to reject the null hypothesis. 
#To conclude, there is no difference of BMI between male and female participants in this 10,000 BRFSS sample.

Chi-square test for categorical variable

#Perform chi-square test to check whether the education attainment is independent from sex
#H0 (Null hypothesis): Off the 10,000 participants of BRFSS 2023, the education attainment is independent from sex (no difference, no association).
#H1 (alternative hypothesis): Off the 10,000 participants of BRFSS 2023, he education attainment is dependent by sex.

#Generate barchart to check the distribution of education by sex

ggplot(data = BRFSS_2023, aes(x = `_EDUCAG`, fill = factor(SEXVAR))) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(
    title = "Education Attainment",
    y = "Count"
  )

#Perform chi-square for 2*5 table
chisq.test(as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR), y = as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$`_EDUCAG`))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$SEXVAR) and as.numeric(BRFSS_2023$`_EDUCAG`)
## X-squared = 52.309, df = 4, p-value = 1.189e-10
#Based on the chi-square test, the p-value of the test was 1.189e-10 = 0.0000000001189, which is less than 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis. 
#To conclude, education attainment is dependent on sex based on the 10,000 participants of BRFSS 2023.
